```

At runtime, the generator reads built-in content from the image and optional site-specific overrides from `/overrides` by default.

## Profile basics

A profile is a YAML file that creates one install menu group in `boot.ipxe`. A profile decides:

- What title appears in the PXE menu.
- Which RHEL versions it supports.
- Whether it is implemented or only a safe placeholder.
- Which Kickstart template should be rendered.
- Which extra kernel arguments should be added.

Example profile:

```yaml
profile_id: minimal
title: Minimal Installs
install_label: Minimal
menu_target: minimal
implemented: true
show_in_main_menu: true
uefi: true
bios: true
supported_os:
  - rhel8
  - rhel9
kickstart_template: ks/{{ os_id }}-minimal.ks.j2
kernel_args:
  - inst.text
  - nomodeset
```

Important rules:

- `profile_id` and `menu_target` must use lowercase letters, numbers, and underscores only.
- Boolean values must be real YAML booleans: `true` or `false`. Do not quote them.
- `implemented: false` creates safe menu placeholders only. It does not create real boot targets or Kickstarts.
- `implemented: true` creates real boot targets and generated Kickstarts for supported detected ISOs.
- `supported_os` can include `rhel7`, `rhel8`, `rhel9`, and `rhel10`.

## Current built-in profile set

The current built-in profile order is:

1. Developer Workstation Installs
2. Security Baseline Installs
3. Security + LUKS Installs
4. Embedded / Edge Hardware Installs
5. Minimal Installs
6. Small Disk Installs

Only profiles marked `implemented: true` generate real boot targets and Kickstarts. The placeholder profiles are shown so users can see planned install paths without accidentally booting unfinished automation.

## Adding a new profile

Use this pattern when adding a new built-in profile to the project.

1. Add a new file under `content/profiles/`.
2. Give it a numbered filename so the menu order is obvious.
3. Add or reuse a Kickstart template under `templates/ks/`.
4. Run the built-in tests before merging.

Example:

```text
content/profiles/70-lab-workstation.yml
templates/ks/rhel8-lab-workstation.ks.j2
templates/ks/rhel9-lab-workstation.ks.j2
templates/ks/rhel10-lab-workstation.ks.j2
```

Example profile:

```yaml
profile_id: lab_workstation
title: Lab Workstation Installs
install_label: Lab Workstation
menu_target: lab_workstation
implemented: true
show_in_main_menu: true
uefi: true
bios: true
supported_os:
  - rhel8
  - rhel9
  - rhel10
kickstart_template: ks/{{ os_id }}-lab-workstation.ks.j2
kernel_args:
  - inst.text
  - nomodeset
```

Then test the image:

```bash
podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test all
```

## Overriding a profile at runtime

Use profile overrides when a site needs different menu text, supported OS choices, firmware support, kernel arguments, or a different Kickstart template without rebuilding the image.

Default override location inside the container:

```text
/overrides/profiles/
```

Example runtime override:

```text
/overrides/profiles/10-minimal.yml
```

If the override file uses an existing `profile_id`, it replaces that built-in profile. If it uses a new `profile_id`, it is added as a new profile.

Example override:

```yaml
profile_id: minimal
title: Site Minimal Installs
install_label: Site Minimal
menu_target: minimal
implemented: true
show_in_main_menu: true
uefi: true
bios: false
supported_os:
  - rhel9
kickstart_template: ks/rhel9-site-minimal.ks.j2
kernel_args:
  - inst.text
  - nomodeset
```

## Overriding a Kickstart template

Use template overrides when the menu/profile is mostly correct but the install content needs to change.

Default override location:

```text
/overrides/templates/ks/
```

Two common approaches are supported.

### Option 1: Replace a template by using the same relative path

For a built-in template like:

```text
templates/ks/rhel8-minimal.ks.j2
```

Create this runtime override:

```text
/overrides/templates/ks/rhel8-minimal.ks.j2
```

The override template wins over the built-in template.

### Option 2: Point a profile override to a new template name

Profile override:

```yaml
kickstart_template: ks/rhel8-site-minimal.ks.j2
```

Template override:

```text
/overrides/templates/ks/rhel8-site-minimal.ks.j2
```

This is cleaner when the site wants a clearly named custom template instead of replacing the built-in template name.

## Template variables

Kickstart templates may use Jinja2 variables from the generator. Common variables include:

```jinja2
{{ os_id }}
{{ os_major }}
{{ os_title }}
{{ profile_id }}
{{ profile_title }}
{{ base_url }}
{{ repo_url }}
{{ kickstart_url }}
{{ rootpw_hash }}
{{ kernel_args_string }}
```

Uppercase versions are also available for simple `$VARIABLE` style templates, such as `$REPO_URL` and `$ROOTPW_HASH`.

## Using Kickstart partials

Built-in templates can include reusable partials from `templates/partials/`:

```jinja2
{% include "partials/install-mode-text.ks.j2" %}
{% include "partials/language-keyboard.ks.j2" %}
{% include "partials/network-dhcp.ks.j2" %}
{% include "partials/root-password.ks.j2" %}
{% include "partials/repo-url.ks.j2" %}
{% include "partials/packages-minimal.ks.j2" %}
```

When writing override templates, prefer using the same partials where possible. That keeps site customizations smaller and makes future changes easier to review.

## Manual or emergency edits under `/ks`

The preferred customization path is always:

```text
/overrides/profiles/
/overrides/templates/
```

However, direct emergency edits under the generated `/ks` directory are supported.

Default behavior:

```text
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=preserve
```

With `preserve`, if someone manually edits a generated Kickstart under `/ks`, the generator does not overwrite it on the next run. Instead, it writes the newly generated version as a candidate file:

```text
/generated/preserved-kickstarts/<kickstart-name>.candidate
```

The state is tracked under:

```text
/generated/kickstart-state/<kickstart-name>.json
```

Use this during emergency troubleshooting when PXE install work must continue before a clean profile/template override can be created.

To force the generator to overwrite manual edits:

```text
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=overwrite
```

Use `overwrite` when the generated source of truth should win and manual edits should be discarded.

## Generated status and index files

The generator writes human-readable and machine-readable status files:

```text
/generated/status.json
/generated/status.txt
/index.html
```

Use `status.json` for automation and troubleshooting. It includes:

- Detected ISO trees.
- Visible and enabled profiles.
- Generated Kickstarts.
- Active profile/template overrides.
- Validation summary and detailed validation results.
- Preserved manual edit state.
- Stale Kickstart cleanup actions.

Use `status.txt` when reading from the command line. Use `index.html` when checking the container from a browser.

## Validation failure policy

The generator always writes status files before enforcing the validation failure policy.

Default behavior:

```text
PXE_VALIDATION_FAILURE_POLICY=warn
```

`warn` means validation errors are reported in status output, but generation does not fail.

Strict behavior:

```text
PXE_VALIDATION_FAILURE_POLICY=fail
```

`fail` means the generator exits non-zero when validation errors exist. This is useful for CI/CD and test scripts.

## Quick test command

After building or pulling the image, run all included tests from inside the image:

```bash
podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test all
```

Run one test at a time:

```bash
podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test basic

podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test overrides

podman run --rm --entrypoint /usr/local/bin/pxe-content-test \
  registry.gitlab.us.lmco.com/lit/containers/pxe-content:test validation
```

Passing tests prove the image can generate PXE content, render profiles/templates, serve generated files, preserve emergency edits, enforce validation policy, and avoid leaking the root password hash into status pages.

## Common troubleshooting

### No ISOs detected

Confirm the ISO tree exists under the configured ISO root and includes:

```text
rhel8iso/images/pxeboot/vmlinuz
rhel8iso/images/pxeboot/initrd.img
```

For RHEL 8, 9, and 10, also confirm repository metadata exists:

```text
BaseOS/repodata/repomd.xml
AppStream/repodata/repomd.xml
```

### Profile file fails to load

Check for quoted booleans or unsupported boolean words.

Correct:

```yaml
implemented: true
```

Incorrect:

```yaml
implemented: "true"
implemented: yes
implemented: on
```

### Override template cannot include partials

Make sure the image still includes the built-in `templates/partials/` directory. Override templates can include built-in partials through the Jinja search path.

### Validation fails because of unresolved Jinja

Look for leftover template syntax in a generated Kickstart:

```text
{% ... %}
{{ ... }}
```

That usually means a template block was intentionally broken, misspelled, or not rendered through Jinja2.

### Manual `/ks` edit will not go away

The default policy preserves manual edits. Regenerate with:

```text
PXE_GENERATED_KS_EDIT_POLICY=overwrite
```

Then rerun the generator.
